st's View of the Right to Communicate -- tThe Right to Communicate as Seen in Developing Countries -- tThe Right to Communicate -- tThe Right to Communicate: The Indonesian Case -- tThe Right to Communicate0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe “right to communicate” is an evolving and expanding concept that was first enunciated in 1969 by Jean d’Arcy. This collection of 22 original essays takes the first comprehensive look at this emerging idea and examines it from the ideologically and culturally varied viewpoints of the contributors.The right to communicate is comprised of all the familiar rights of press, speech, opinion--as found in Article 19 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights--as well as of the concerns for privacy, and access to media and information. But as the essays here show, the right to communicate is more than a collection or reorganization of familiar rights, going far beyond them so as to merit being called a “new human right.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aArmando Cocca, Aldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampeanu, Pavel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassirer, Henry R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFirsov, B. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox De Cardona, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillmor, Donald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarms, L. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarms, L. S